{"title_page": "Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.", "text_new": "{{Infobox COA case\n  |Litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.\n  |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n  |CourtSeal=\n  |ArgueDate=February 9,\n  |ArgueYear=2009\n  |ReargueDate=December 15,\n  |ReargueYear=2009\n  |DecideDate=September 8,\n  |DecideYear=2010\n  |FullName=Binyam Mohamed, et al., v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.\n  |Citations=[https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ 614 F.3d 1070]\n  |Prior=[https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081667539fsupp2d112811557 539 F. Supp. 2d 1128] ([[United States District Court for the Northern District of California|N.D. Cal.]] 2008); [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1358830/mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ 579 F.3d 943] (9th Cir. 2009)\n  |Subsequent=[[Certiorari|Cert.]] denied, May 16, 2011\n  |Holding=\n  |Judges=[[Alex Kozinski]], [[Mary M. Schroeder]], [[William C. Canby]], [[Michael Daly Hawkins]], [[Sidney R. Thomas]], [[Raymond C. Fisher]], [[Richard A. Paez]], [[Richard C. Tallman]], [[Johnnie B. Rawlinson]], [[Consuelo M. Callahan]], [[Carlos T. Bea]]\n  |Majority=Fisher\n  |JoinMajority=Kozinski, Tallman, Rawlinson, Callahan, Bea\n  |Concurrence=Bea\n  |Dissent=Hawkins\n  |JoinDissent=Schroeder, Canby, Thomas, Paez\n  |LawsApplied=\n}}\n\n'''''Mohamed et al. v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.''''', is a case brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) on behalf of five victims of [[Extraordinary rendition by the United States|extraordinary rendition]]s against [[Jeppesen|Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.]], which had provided services that the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) used to perform renditions.\n\n==Background==\nAccording to an article that appeared in October 2006 in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', the CIA is a Jeppesen customer. The article claims that the company has provided navigational and logistics support to the agency's extraordinary rendition program.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/10/30/061030ta_talk_mayer\n|title=Outsourcing: The C.I.A.\u2019s Travel Agent\n|author=Jane Mayer\n|work=The New Yorker\n|date=October 30, 2006\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n}}</ref> The article says Jeppesen provided \"flight plans, clearance to fly over other countries, hotel reservations, and ground-crew arrangements\" to the CIA. According to the article, an unnamed former employee quoted Bob Overby, Jeppesen's managing director, as saying at a meeting, \"We do all of the extraordinary renditions flights\u2014you know, the torture flights. ... Let's face it, some of those flights end up that way... It certainly pays well.\"<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.aclu.org/safefree/rendition/33223lgl20071015.html\n |title=Declaration of Sean Belcher\n|author=Sean Belcher\n|date=October 15, 2007\n|format=PDF\n|accessdate=February 9, 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306033737/http://www.aclu.org/safefree/rendition/33223lgl20071015.html |archivedate = March 6, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2006, [[Amnesty International]] staged a demonstration in front of the company's International Trip and Flight Planning Office in [[San Jose, California]] to protest their involvement in the rendition program.<ref>[http://www.amnestyusa.org/events/western/11172006grp35_highlight.html Demonstration at Jeppesen Corporation in San Jose, California]. Amnesty International. November 17, 2006.</ref> In December 2006 representatives of the South Bay Mobilization for Peace and Justice group asked the San Jose City Council to remove a Jeppesen banner from a city skating rink. The group also holds a weekly vigil at the company's offices.<ref>[http://www.metroactive.com/metro/12.13.06/fly-0650.html Silicon Valley News Notes: Icecapade]. Metro Newspapers. December 13, 2006.</ref>\n\n==ACLU lawsuit==\n\nOn May 30, 2007, the ACLU sued Jeppesen on behalf of five [[plaintiff]]s who had been tortured in [[Morocco]], [[Egypt]] and a United States base in [[Afghanistan]]. The suit alleged that, since 2001, Jeppesen provided support for at least seventy flights for the CIA's secret extraordinary rendition program, transporting prisoners overseas to be tortured.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/05/31/boeing_subsidiary_accused_of_aiding_cia_torture_flights/\n|title=Boeing subsidiary accused of aiding CIA torture flights\n|author=Henry Weinstein\n|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]\n|date=May 31, 2007\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n}}</ref> The suit was dismissed in February 2008 on a motion from the [[United States]] government, on the theory that proceeding with the case would reveal [[Classified information|state secret]]s and endanger [[diplomacy|relations]] with other nations that had cooperated.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc. |vol=539 |reporter=F.Supp.2d |opinion=1128 |pinpoint= |court=N.D. Cal. |date=2008 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081667539fsupp2d112811557 |accessdate=2017-10-09 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/02/13/BAVIV270H.DTL\n|title=Federal judge dismisses suit over torture flights\n|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n|author=Bob Egelko\n|date=February 13, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8, 2010, in a 6\u20135 [[en banc]] ruling, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] affirmed the dismissal of the suit,<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc. |vol=614 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1070 |pinpoint= |court=9th. Cir. |date=2010 |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ |accessdate=2017-10-09 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author= Charlie Savage | title= Court Dismisses a Case Asserting Torture by C.I.A. | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/09/us/09secrets.html&pagewanted=all | work= [[The New York Times]] | date= September 8, 2010 | accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref> and the ACLU filed an appeal with the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Test of 'state secrets' shield goes before Supreme Court |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/2011-01-17-courtsecrets17_ST_N.htm |author=Joan Biskupic |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 17, 2011 |accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2011, the Supreme Court declined to review the decision of the Ninth Circuit to dismiss the case.<ref>{{citation |title=Order List 563 U.S. |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/051611zor.pdf |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.'', 579 F.3d 943 (9th Cir. 2009)\n | cornell =\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1358830/mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/\n | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-9th-circuit/1461839.html\n | justia =http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/08-15693/08-15693-2011-02-25.html\n | oyez =\n | vlex =\n | googlescholar =https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=13327448145372310874\n | leagle =https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20090831115\n }}\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.'', 614 F.3d 1070 (9th. Cir. 2010)\n | cornell =\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/\n | findlaw = \n | justia =\n | oyez =\n | vlex =\n | googlescholar =https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1060445994998403010\n | leagle =https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20100909129\n | other_source1 = 9th Cir.\n | other_url1 =http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2010/09/08/08-15693.pdf\n }}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mohamed Et Al. V. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.}}\n[[Category:Boeing]]\n[[Category:United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit cases]]\n[[Category:United States tort case law]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox COA case\n  |Litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.\n  |Court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n  |CourtSeal=\n  |ArgueDate=February 9,\n  |ArgueYear=2009\n  |ReargueDate=December 15,\n  |ReargueYear=2009\n  |DecideDate=September 8,\n  |DecideYear=2010\n  |FullName=Binyam Mohamed, et al., v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.\n  |Citations=[https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ 614 F.3d 1070]\n  |Prior=[https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081667539fsupp2d112811557 539 F. Supp. 2d 1128] ([[United States District Court for the Northern District of California|N.D. Cal.]] 2008); [https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1358830/mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ 579 F.3d 943] (9th Cir. 2009)\n  |Subsequent=[[Certiorari|Cert.]] denied, May 16, 2011\n  |Holding=\n  |Judges=[[Alex Kozinski]], [[Mary M. Schroeder]], [[William C. Canby]], [[Michael Daly Hawkins]], [[Sidney R. Thomas]], [[Raymond C. Fisher]], [[Richard A. Paez]], [[Richard C. Tallman]], [[Johnnie B. Rawlinson]], [[Consuelo M. Callahan]], [[Carlos T. Bea]]\n  |Majority=Fisher\n  |JoinMajority=Kozinski, Tallman, Rawlinson, Callahan, Bea\n  |Concurrence=Bea\n  |Dissent=Hawkins\n  |JoinDissent=Schroeder, Canby, Thomas, Paez\n  |LawsApplied=\n}}\n\n'''''Mohamed et al. v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.''''', is a case brought by the [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) on behalf of five victims of [[Extraordinary rendition by the United States|extraordinary rendition]]s against [[Jeppesen|Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.]], which had provided services that the [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) used to perform renditions.\n\n==Background==\nAccording to an article that appeared in October 2006 in ''[[The New Yorker]]'', the CIA is a Jeppesen customer. The article claims that the company has provided navigational and logistics support to the agency's extraordinary rendition program.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/10/30/061030ta_talk_mayer\n|title=Outsourcing: The C.I.A.\u2019s Travel Agent\n|author=Jane Mayer\n|work=The New Yorker\n|date=October 30, 2006\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n}}</ref> The article says Jeppesen provided \"flight plans, clearance to fly over other countries, hotel reservations, and ground-crew arrangements\" to the CIA. According to the article, an unnamed former employee quoted Bob Overby, Jeppesen's managing director, as saying at a meeting, \"We do all of the extraordinary renditions flights\u2014you know, the torture flights. ... Let's face it, some of those flights end up that way... It certainly pays well.\"<ref>{{cite web\n|url=https://www.aclu.org/safefree/rendition/33223lgl20071015.html\n |title=Declaration of Sean Belcher\n|author=Sean Belcher\n|date=October 15, 2007\n|format=PDF\n|accessdate=February 9, 2009 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306033737/http://www.aclu.org/safefree/rendition/33223lgl20071015.html |archivedate = March 6, 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn November 16, 2006, [[Amnesty International]] staged a demonstration in front of the company's International Trip and Flight Planning Office in [[San Jose, California]] to protest their involvement in the rendition program.<ref>[http://www.amnestyusa.org/events/western/11172006grp35_highlight.html Demonstration at Jeppesen Corporation in San Jose, California]. Amnesty International. November 17, 2006.</ref> In December 2006 representatives of the South Bay Mobilization for Peace and Justice group asked the San Jose City Council to remove a Jeppesen banner from a city skating rink. The group also holds a weekly vigil at the company's offices.<ref>[http://www.metroactive.com/metro/12.13.06/fly-0650.html Silicon Valley News Notes: Icecapade]. Metro Newspapers. December 13, 2006.</ref>\n\n==ACLU lawsuit==\n\nOn May 30, 2007, the ACLU sued Jeppesen on behalf of five [[plaintiff]]s who had been tortured in [[Morocco]], [[Egypt]] and a United States base in [[Afghanistan]]. The suit alleged that, since 2001, Jeppesen provided support for at least seventy flights for the CIA's secret extraordinary rendition program, transporting prisoners overseas to be tortured.<ref>{{cite news\n|url=http://www.boston.com/news/nation/articles/2007/05/31/boeing_subsidiary_accused_of_aiding_cia_torture_flights/\n|title=Boeing subsidiary accused of aiding CIA torture flights\n|author=Henry Weinstein\n|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]\n|date=May 31, 2007\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n}}</ref> The suit was dismissed in February 2008 on a motion from the [[United States]] government, on the theory that proceeding with the case would reveal [[Classified information|state secret]]s and endanger [[diplomacy|relations]] with other nations that had cooperated.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc. |vol=539 |reporter=F.Supp.2d |opinion=1128 |pinpoint= |court=N.D. Cal. |date=2008 |url=https://www.leagle.com/decision/20081667539fsupp2d112811557 |accessdate=2017-10-09 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2008/02/13/BAVIV270H.DTL\n|title=Federal judge dismisses suit over torture flights\n|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]\n|accessdate=February 2, 2011\n|author=Bob Egelko\n|date=February 13, 2008\n}}</ref>\n\nOn September 8, 2010, in a 6\u20135 [[en banc]] ruling, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]] affirmed the dismissal of the suit,<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc. |vol=614 |reporter=F.3d |opinion=1070 |pinpoint= |court=9th. Cir. |date=2010 |url=https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/ |accessdate=2017-10-09 |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | author= Charlie Savage | title= Court Dismisses a Case Asserting Torture by C.I.A. | url= https://www.nytimes.com/2010/09/09/us/09secrets.html&pagewanted=all | work= [[The New York Times]] | date= September 8, 2010 | accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref> and the ACLU filed an appeal with the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] in December 2010.<ref>{{cite news |title=Test of 'state secrets' shield goes before Supreme Court |url=https://www.usatoday.com/news/washington/judicial/2011-01-17-courtsecrets17_ST_N.htm |author=Joan Biskupic |work=[[USA Today]] |date=January 17, 2011 |accessdate=February 2, 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn May 16, 2011, the Supreme Court declined to review the decision of the Ninth Circuit to dismiss the case.<ref>{{citation |title=Order List 563 U.S. |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/orders/courtorders/051611zor.pdf |date=May 16, 2011 |accessdate=May 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.'', 579 F.3d 943 (9th Cir. 2009)\n | cornell =\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/1358830/mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/\n | findlaw = https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-9th-circuit/1461839.html\n | justia =http://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/08-15693/08-15693-2011-02-25.html\n | oyez =\n | vlex =\n | other_source1 = Google Scholar\n | other_url1 =https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=13327448145372310874\n | other_source2 = Leagle\n | other_url2 =https://www.leagle.com/decision/infco20090831115\n | other_source3 = \n | other_url3 =\n | other_source4 = \n | other_url4 =\n | other_source5 = \n | other_url5 =\n | other_source6 = \n | other_url6 =\n | other_source7 = \n | other_url7 =\n | other_source8 = \n | other_url8 =\n | other_source9 = \n | other_url9 =\n }}\n* {{caselaw source\n | case = ''Mohamed v. Jeppesen Dataplan, Inc.'', 614 F.3d 1070 (9th. Cir. 2010)\n | cornell =\n | courtlistener =https://www.courtlistener.com/opinion/174989/binyam-mohamed-v-jeppesen-dataplan-inc/\n | findlaw = \n | justia =\n | oyez =\n | vlex =\n | other_source1 = Google Scholar\n | other_url1 =https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=1060445994998403010\n | other_source2 =