{"title_page": "Roman Catholic Diocese of Conversano-Monopoli", "text_new": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Conversano-Monopoli\n| latin             = Dioecesis Conversanensis-Monopolitana\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Conversano03.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral in [[Conversano]]\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = Italy\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto|Bari-Bitonto]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 1,099 \n| population        = 252,707\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 249,650 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 98.8\n| parishes          = 56<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 5th Century \n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di S. Maria Assunta\n| cocathedral       = Basilica Cattedrale di Maria SS. della Mactia\n| patron            = \n| priests           = 94 (diocesan)<br />49 (Religious Orders)<br />17 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Giuseppe Favale]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Regione ecclesiastica Puglia.PNG\n| map_alt           = Regional map of dioceses of east coast of Italy\n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it/ www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe Italian Roman Catholic '''diocese of Conversano-Monopoli''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Conversanensis-Monopolitana}}), in [[Apulia]], has existed since 1986, when the [[diocese of Monopoli]] was united with the historic '''diocese of Conversano'''. The diocese is a [[suffragan]] of the [[Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto]].<ref name=CathHierMazaraConversano>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dconv.html \"Diocese of Conversano-Monopoli\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathConversano>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/conv0.htm \"Diocese of Conversano\u2013Monopoli\"]  ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[Conversano]] is the ancient [[Cupersanum]]. After the invasion of the Normans, it was for a while the seat of a duchy; later, however, it became a fief of the [[dukes of Atri]].\n\nLocal tradition preserves the name of a bishop, Simplicius, who attended the Roman synod of 487 and died in 492, but he belongs to legend, not history.<ref>Lanzoni, p. 303, who notes that his name is not found in the acta of that synod.</ref> Ferdinando Ughelli<ref>''Italia sacra'' VII, p. 701.</ref> prints the narrative of Francesco Giuliano of Conversano concerning Simplicius, but states that it seems to him to be highly suspect, and maybe deliberately invented falsehoods or corrupt, since there are some things found in it which cannot be true.<ref>''...mihi valde suspecta videtur, et forte commentitia vel corrupta, cum in ea aliqua sint apposita quae cum veritate esse non possunt.''</ref>\n\nThe first alleged bishop of Conversano was [[Hilarius (bishop, fl. 501)|Hilarius]], present at the Roman synod of 501. His name however is a false reading of the acts of the synod; he actually belonged to Tempsa in the Abruzzi, not to Conversano in Apulia.\n\nNo other names are recorded up to the episcopate of Leo, mentioned in a document of 1088.\n\nIn 1670 (and 1744) the Chapter of the Cathedral of the Assumption of the Body of the Blessed Virgin Mary into Heaven was composed of four dignities (the Archdeacon, the Archpriest, the Cantor and the Primicerius<ref>Ughelli, p. 700.</ref>) and twenty-six Canons.<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 note 1; VI, p. 181 note 1. Ughelli says there were twelve Canons.</ref>  In the city of approximately 7,000 inhabitants (1744) there were five religious houses for men and three monasteries for men.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Conversano===\n====to 1400====\n:'''...'''\n* Leo (attested 1088)<ref>Leo granted the spiritual jurisdiction of Castrum Puteneanum to the monastery of S. Stefano  in Monopoli. Ughelli, p. 704. Graevius-Burmann, pp. 39, 69.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Cafisius (attested 1179, 1180)<ref>Ughelli, p. 704. Kamp, p. 626.</ref>\n*Guilelmus (attested 1188 \u2013 April 1202)<ref>Ughelli, pp. 704-705. Kamp, p. 626.</ref>\n*''Ignotus'' (attested 1207)<ref>Kamp, pp. 626-627.</ref>\n*Concilius (attested April 1212 \u2013 9 October 1231)<ref>Kamp, pp. 627-628.</ref>\n* Stefano, O.Cist. (attested 1267 \u2013 1274)<ref name=NewAdvent>Umberto Benigni. \"[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04346a.htm Conversano].\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 4. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1908. Retrieved: 2016-10-02.  Ughelli, VII, pp. 705-708. Kamp, pp. 628-629.</ref>\n;'''...'''\n* Giovanni de Gropi (c. 1283)<ref>Gropi: Ughelli, pp. 711-712. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n;'''...'''\n* Guillelmus (attested 1318, 1321)<ref>Guillelmus: Gams, p. 877. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Petrus Baccari (attested 1335, 1342)<ref>Petrus Baccari: Gams, p. 877. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Stefano (7 January 1351 \u2013 1355?)<ref>Stefano: Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Petrus de Ytro (19 February 1356 \u2013 )\n* Guilelmus (Avignon Obedience)\n* Angelo de Cupersano, O.Min. (12 July 1393 \u2013 ) (Avignon Obedience)<ref>Angelo had previously been Bishop of Polignano (1382\u20131393). Eubel, I, pp. 218, 405.</ref>\n* Amicus (Antonius) (Roman Obedience)\n* Jacobus ( \u2013 22 December 1399) (Roman Obedience)<ref>Jacobus was transferred to the diocese of Guardialfiera on 22 December 1399. Eubel, I, pp. 218, 269.</ref>\n\n====1400 to 1600====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Franciscus\n*Stefano de Alfano (9 March 1403 \u2013 1423)<ref>Stefano: Ughelli, p. 412. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n*Antonio Guidotti (9 Sep 1423 \u2013 1432 Died)<ref>Antonio was the son of Guidotti, a notary of Conversano. He was Archdeacon of Conversano when appointed bishop by [[Pope Martin IV]]. Ughelli, p. 412. Cappelletti, XXI, p. 42. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n:*Marino Orsini (4 November 1432 \u2013 29 April 1437) (Administrator)<ref>Orsini, son of Francesco Orsini, was a member of the aristocratic Roman family of the Orsini. He was a Doctor of Canon Law and a Protonotary Apostolic. On 4 July 1444 he was named Archbishop of Palermo, and then Archbishop of Taranto on 30 July 1445. He served as papal Nuncio in England. {{cite book|author=Jean Guiraud|title=L'\u00e9tat pontifical apr\u00e8s le grand schisme: \u00e9tude de g\u00e9ographie politique|url=https://archive.org/details/ltatpontificala00guirgoog|year=1896|publisher=A. Fontemoing|location=Paris|language=French|page=[https://archive.org/details/ltatpontificala00guirgoog/page/n134 116]}} Eubel, II, p. 136 with note 1; 211; 246.</ref>\n*[[Andrea Veroli]] (29 Apr 1437 \u2013 25 Sep 1439)<ref>Veroli was appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Campobasso-Boiano|Bishop of Boiano]] on 25 September 1439. Eubel, II, pp. 108, 135.</ref><ref name=CathHierAndVer>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bverul.html \"Bishop Andrea Veroli\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved May 10, 2017</ref>\n* Donato Bottini, [[O.E.S.A.]] (9 October 1439 \u2013 4 September 1448)<ref>A Neapolitan, Bishop Donato was transferred to the diocese of Valva on 4 September 1448. He was later Bishop of Urbino (1452), and Camerino (1464). Eubel, II, pp. 135, 262.</ref>\n*Pietro de Miggola, [[Order of Minims|O.M.]] (4 September 1448 \u2013 1464)<ref>Pietro was a Spaniard, and had been papal Penitentiary Minor. Ughelli, VII, p. 713.</ref>\n*Paolo de Torcoli (30 November 1465 \u2013 d. 1482)<ref>Torcoli was Capitular Vicar during the vacancy following the death of Bishop Pietro de Miggola. He was appointed bishop by [[Pope Paul II]] at the request of Count Giulio Acquaviva and Countess Catherine. Ughelli, p. 713. Eubel, II, p. 135.</ref>\n*[[Sulpicio Acquaviva d'Aragona]] (17 Feb 1483 \u2013 1494 Died)<ref>Sulpicio Acquaviva was the son of Giulio Antonio Acquaviva and Caterina d'Atri. The family of Acquaviva had been Counts of Conversano since the fifteenth century: {{cite book|author=Casimiro : di S. Maria Maddalena padre (padre)|title=Cronica della provincia de' Minori Osservanti Scalzi di S. Pietro d'Alcantara nel Regno di Napoli |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_zgSqJ-xk6ykC|year=1729|publisher=a spese di d. Lelio di Cabano|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_zgSqJ-xk6ykC/page/n485 466]\u2013468}} {{cite book|author=Pierfrancesco Rescio|title=La Cattedrale di Conversano|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3PFHP07BDksC&pg=PA51|year=2001|publisher=Rubbettino Editore|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-498-0094-4|page=51}}</ref><ref name=CathHierSulpAcqua>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bacqdaras.html \"Bishop Sulpicio Acquaviva d'Aragona\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Pistacchio]] (1494 \u2013 3 Nov 1499 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Bitetto|Bishop of Bitetto]])<ref name=CathHierVinPista>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bpistacc.html \"Bishop Vincenzo Pistacchio\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Donato Acquaviva d'Aragona]] (1499 \u2013 1528 Died)<ref>Donato was the brother of the Marquis de Bitonto and of Bishop Sulpicio Acquaviva.  Donato d'Aragona was appointed Bishop of Conversano at the age of 24, and thus was only ''Administrator'' of the diocese for three years, until he reached the age of 27, when he could be consecrated in accordance with Canon Law. He held the rank of Protonotary Apostolic. Eubel, II, p. 135, with note 3.</ref><ref name=CathHierDonAcqAra>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bacqdarad.html \"Bishop Donato Acquaviva d'Aragona\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*[[Antonio Sanseverino]], [[O.S.Io.Hieros.]] (28 Jul 1529 \u2013 11 Feb 1534 Resigned) \n*[[Giacomo Antonio Carrozza]] (1534 \u2013 1560 Died)<ref name=CathHierGiaAntCar>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcarroz.html \"Bishop Giacomo Antonio Carrozza\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*[[Giovanni Francesco Lottini]] (1560 \u2013 1561 Resigned) \n*[[Romolo de Valentibus]] (1561 \u2013 1579 Died)<ref name=CathHierRomValen>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bvlntbs.html \"Bishop Romolo de Valentibus\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*Francesco Maria Sforza (1579 \u2013 1605 Died)<ref>Francesco Sforza was a native of Monopoli and a doctor of theology. Ughelli, VII, p. 715. Eubel, III, p. 177.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====1600 to 1800====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Pietro Capullio]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (31 Aug 1605 \u2013 24 Jun 1625 Died)<ref>Capulli was a native of Cortone. He was regent of the school at the convent of the Franciscans at the Basilica XII Apostolorum in Rome. He was named bishop of Conversano by [[Pope Paul V]] on 31 August 1605, and consecrated by Cardinal Evangelista Palotto on 14 September 1605. He died on 24 June 1625. Ughelli, p. 715. Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Martinelli (bishop)]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (18 Aug 1625 \u2013 20 Sep 1632)<ref>Bishop Martinelli was transferred to the diocese of  [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Venafro|Venafro]] on 20 September 1632. He died in August 1635. Gauchat, IV, pp. 163 with note 3; 361 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Antonio Brunachio]] (24 Nov 1632 \u2013 1 Jan 1638 Died)<ref>Brunachio: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Agostino Ferentillo]] (19 Apr 1638 \u2013 7 Sep 1641 Died)<ref>Ferentillo: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Pietro Paolo Bonsi]] (26 May 1642 \u2013 1658 Died)<ref>Bonsi: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 6.</ref>\n*[[Giuseppe Palermo]] (8 Dec 1658 \u2013 1 Sep 1670)<ref>Palermo was transferred to the diocese of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santa Severina|Santa Severina]] on 1 September 1670. He died in 1673. Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 7. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 355 with note 2.</ref>\n* Giovanni Stefano Sanarica (Senarega), [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (23 Feb 1671 \u2013 16 Jun 1679 Died)<ref>Senarega was born in Albaro (diocese of Genoa). He held a doctorate in theology (Parma 1663). He was consecrated in Rome on 8 March 1671 by Cardinal Carlo Roberti. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 with note 2.</ref> \n*[[Andrea Brancaccio]], [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (13 Jan 1681 \u2013 18 Apr 1701)<ref>Appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cosenza-Bisignano|Archbishop of Cosenza]]. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 171 with note 3; 179 with note 4.</ref><ref name=CathHierNicCir>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcirillo.html \"Bishop Nicola Cirillo\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved August 21, 2016.{{self-published inline|date=March 2017}}</ref>\n*Filippo Meda (23 Jan 1702 \u2013 18 Jul 1733 Died)<ref>Meda: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 with note 4.</ref>\n*Giovanni Macario Valenti (28 Sep 1733 \u2013 10 Apr 1744 Died)<ref>Valenti: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 2.</ref>\n*Filippo Felice del Prete (13 Apr 1744 \u2013 22 Dec 1751 Died)<ref>Del Prete: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 3.</ref>\n*Michele di Tarsia, [[C.P.O.]] (24 Jan 1752 \u2013 7 May 1772 Died)<ref>Born in 1696, Tarsia was a native of Conversano, and was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (La Sapienza, Rome, 1752) at the age of 48. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 30 January 1752 by the titular Patriarch of Constantinople, Ferdinando Maria Rossi. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 4.</ref>\n*Fabio Maria Palumbo, [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (7 Sep 1772 \u2013 18 Mar 1786 Died)<ref>Palumbo was born in 1708 at Lecce. He taught theology in several houses of his Congregation. He was Vicar of the house of his Congregation at S. Andrea della Valle in Rome. He was consecrated in Rome by Cardinal Ferdinando Maria Rossi on 13 September 1772. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 5.</ref>\n*Nicola Vecchi (27 Feb 1792 \u2013 18 Dec 1797)<ref>Vecchi was appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Teano|Bishop of Teano]] by Ferdinand I, King of the Two Sicilies, on 24 October 1797, and confirmed by Pope Pius VI on 18 December 1797. Ritzler-Sefrin, pp. 181 with note 6; 399 with note 8.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====1800 to 1986====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Gennaro Carelli (18 Dec 1797 \u2013 3 Mar 1818 Died)<ref>Carelli was a native of Conversano. He held the degree of ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Naples 1771). He was Canon, then Primicerius, and finally Archpriest of the Chapter of the Cathedral of Conversano. He was nominated bishop on 31 October 1797 by King [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies]], and approved by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 18 December 1797. Carelli was consecrated in Rome on 24 December 1797 by Cardinal Giovanni Battista Caprara. Luigi Valvalle, in D'Avino, p. 221. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 7.</ref>\n*Nicola Carelli (21 Feb 1820 \u2013 14 Apr 1826 Died)<ref>Nicola Carelli was the brother of Bishop Gennaro Carelli.</ref>\n*Giovanni De Simone, [[Congregation of the Mission|C.M.]] (3 Jul 1826 \u2013 13 Aug 1847 Died)\n*Giuseppe-Maria Mucedola (11 Dec 1848 \u2013 22 Mar 1865 Died)<ref>Mucedola was born in San Paolo (diocese of Santa Severina) in 1807. As bishop, in 1861 he defended the right of the people to make their own political choices in a referendum on the Kingdom of Italy. {{cite book|author=Pietro Scoppola|title=Chiesa e Stato nella storia d'Italia: Storia documentaria dall'Unit\u0101 alla Republica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eoUcAAAAMAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Ed. Laterza|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=142}} {{cite book|author=Cosmo Francesco Ruppi|title=Giuseppe Maria Mucedola: vescovo-patriota di Conversano : con document inediti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-DQQAQAAIAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Scuola Tip. Istituto Provinciale Apicella|location=Molfetta (Bari)|language=Italian}}</ref>\n*Salvatore Silvestris, [[C.SS.R.]] (23 Feb 1872 \u2013 14 Feb 1879 Died)\n*Augusto Antonio Vicentini (12 May 1879 \u2013 13 May 1881)<ref>Vicentini was born in L'Aquila in 1829. He was appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of L'Aquila|Archbishop of L\u2019Aquila]] on 13 May 1881. ''La Gerarchia cattolica 1882'' (Rome: Monaldi 1882), p. 108.</ref>\n*[[Casimiro Gennari]] (13 May 1881 \u2013 6 Feb 1897)<ref>Gennari was a native of Maratea (diocese of Policastro). He was the founder of the monthly journal ''Il Monitore ecclesiastico'', and was a noted author of books on ecclesiastical topics. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 15 May 1881 by Cardinal Edward Howard. He was appointed Titular Archbishop of Naupactus on 6 February 1897, and was named a Cardinal by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 15 April 1901.  Gennari was a collaborator in the creation of the 1917 Pio-Benedictine Code of Canon Law. As a Cardinal, and particularly as Prefect of the SC of the Council, he pressed for frequent reception of communion. He died on 31 January 1914. {{cite book|author=Joseph Dougherty|title=From Altar-Throne to Table: The Campaign for Frequent Holy Communion in the Catholic Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E3ZaJeZj-AsC&pg=PA83|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD USA|isbn=978-0-8108-7092-5|pages=82\u201383}} {{cite book|author=Harris M. Lentz III|title=Popes and Cardinals of the 20th Century: A Biographical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jXEwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA216|year=2001|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, NC USA|isbn=978-0-7864-4101-3|page=79}} G. di Ruocco, ''Il Cardinale Casimiro Gennari. Pastore e giurista (1839\u20131914) (Naples: Laurentiana 1995).</ref>\n*Antonio Lamberti (19 Apr 1897 \u2013 12 Aug 1917 Died)\n*Domenico Lancellotti (14 Mar 1918 \u2013 9 Jun 1930 Died)\n*Domenico Argnani (30 Sep 1931 \u2013 15 Jun 1935)<ref>Argnani was appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Macerata-Tolentino|Bishop of Macerata e Tolentino]] on 15 Jun 1935.</ref>\n*Gregorio Falconieri (12 Sep 1935 \u2013 24 May 1964 Retired)\n*Antonio D'Erchia (21 Jan 1970 \u2013 30 Sep 1986) (Appointed Bishop of the renamed Conversano-Monopoli)\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[File:Cattedrale 008.JPG|thumb|160px|Co-cathedral in [[Monopoli]]]]\n\n===Diocese of Conversano-Monopoli===\n''United: 30 September 1986 with [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Monopoli|Diocese of Monopoli]]''\n*Antonio D'Erchia (30 Sep 1986 \u2013 11 Feb 1987 Retired)\n*[[Domenico Padovano]] (13 Feb 1987 \u2013 5 Feb 2016 Retired) \n*Giuseppe Favale (5 Feb 2016 \u2013 )<ref>Diocesi di Conversano Monopoli, [http://www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it/vescovo/ ''S. E. Mons Giuseppe Favale''], retrieved: 2017-03-12.{{in lang|it}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n===Reference Works===\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 2|date=1914|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 3|date=1923|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol02eubeuoft}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gams|first=Pius Bonifatius |title=Series episcoporum Ecclesiae catholicae: quotquot innotuerunt a beato Petro apostolo|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=os9DAQAAMAAJ|year=1873|publisher=Typis et Sumptibus Georgii Josephi Manz|location=Ratisbon}} pp.&nbsp;946\u2013947. (Use with caution; obsolete)\n*{{cite book|last1=Gauchat|first1=Patritius (Patrice)|title=Hierarchia catholica  IV (1592-1667)|date=1935|publisher=Libraria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol04eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  V (1667-1730)|date=1952|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol05eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentis aevi  VI (1730-1799)|date=1958|publisher=Messagero di S. Antonio|location=Patavii|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol06eubeuoft|accessdate=2016-07-06}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Ritzler|first1=Remigius|last2=Sefrin|first2=Pirminus|title=Hierarchia Catholica medii et recentioris aevi sive summorum pontificum, S. R. E. cardinalium, ecclesiarum antistitum series... A pontificatu Pii PP. VII (1800) usque ad pontificatum Gregorii PP. XVI (1846)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pgyItwAACAAJ|volume=Volume VII|year=1968|publisher=Libr. Regensburgiana|location=Monasterii|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|author1=Ritzler, Remigius|author2=Pirminus Sefrin|title=Hierarchia catholica Medii et recentioris aevi... A Pontificatu PII PP. IX (1846) usque ad Pontificatum Leonis PP. XIII (1903)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5oXUjwEACAAJ|year=1978|volume=Volume VIII|publisher=Il Messaggero di S. Antonio|language=Latin}}\n*{{cite book|last= Pi\u0119ta|first=Zenon|title=Hierarchia catholica medii et recentioris aevi...  A pontificatu Pii PP. X (1903) usque ad pontificatum Benedictii PP. XV (1922)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QXuJQwAACAAJ|volume=Volume IX|year=2002|publisher=Messagero di San Antonio|location=Padua|language=Latin|isbn=978-88-250-1000-8}}\n\n===Studies===\n*{{cite book|last=Avino|first=Vincenzio d' |title=Cenni storici sulle chiese arcivescovili, vescovili, e prelatizie (nullius) del regno delle due Sicilie |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fUIsAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA168|year=1848|publisher=dalle stampe di Ranucci|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=220\u2013221}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Graevius|first1=Joannes Georgius|last2=Burmann|first2=Peter|title=Thesaurus antiquitatum et historiarum Italiae ...: Campaniae, Neapolis, Magnae Graeciae ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2RvHlP6NRA8C&pg=PA106-IA49|volume=Tomi Noni, Pars Quinta (IX.5)|year=1723|publisher=Petrus Vander Aa|location=Lugduni Batavorum|language=Latin|pages=68\u201376}}\n*Kamp, Norbert (1975). ''Kirche und Monarchie im staufischen K\u00f6nigreich Sizilien: [http://digi20.digitale-sammlungen.de/de/fs1/object/display/bsb00042154_00001.html?prox=true&phone=true&ngram=true&seriesTitle_str=%7BKirche+und+Monarchie+im+staufischen+K%C3%B6nigreich+Sizilien%7D&hl=scan&fulltext=Kamp+Kirche+und+Monarchie&mode=simple&context=Kamp%20Kirche%20und%20Monarchie I. Prosopographische Grundlegung, Bistumer und  Bist\u00fcmer und Bisch\u00f6fe des Konigreichs 1194\u20131266: 2. Apulien und Calabrien]'' M\u00fcnchen: Wilhelm Fink 1975.\n*Kehr, Paulus Fridolin (1962). ''Italia pontificia. Regesta pontificum Romanorum.'' [http://sul-derivatives.stanford.edu/derivative?CSNID=00002440&mediaType=application/pdf Vol. IX: Samnia \u2013 Apulia \u2013 Lucania].  Berlin: Weidmann. (in Latin), pp.&nbsp;358\u2013368.\n*{{cite book|author=Lanzoni, Francesco|title=Le diocesi d'Italia dalle origini al principio del secolo VII (an. 604)|url=https://archive.org/details/MN5017ucmf_0|year=1927|publisher=Biblioteca Apostolica Vaticana|location=Rome|language=Italian|pages=}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rescio|first=Pierfrancesco|title=La Cattedrale di Conversano|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3PFHP07BDksC&pg=PA219|year=2001|publisher=Rubbettino Editore|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-498-0094-4}}\n*{{cite book|author=Sante Simone|title=Il mostro della Puglia: ossia, la storia del celebre Monastero di S. Benedetto di Conversano|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1zM_AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA198|year=1885|publisher=Tip. Fratelli Pansini fu S.|location=Bari|language=Italian}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Ughelli|first1=Ferdinando|last2=Coleti|first2=Niccol\u00f2|title=Italia sacra,  sive De Episcopis Italiae|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VfyRMcKY2qgC|volume=Tomus septimus (VII)|year=1721|publisher=apud Sebastianum Coleti|location=Venice|language=Latin|pages=700\u2013720}}\n\n====Acknowledgment====\n::{{Catholic|title=Conversano}}\n{{Roman Catholic Ecclesiastical Province of Bari-Bitonto}}\n\n{{coord|40.9667|N|17.1167|E|source:wikidata-and-enwiki-cat-tree_region:IT|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Roman Catholic dioceses in Apulia|Conversano]]\n[[Category:Monopoli|Diocese Conversano Monopoli]]\n[[Category:Dioceses established in the 5th century|Conversano]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox diocese\n| jurisdiction      = Diocese<!-- Type of jurisdiction: i.e. Diocese or Archdiocese -->\n| name              = Conversano-Monopoli\n| latin             = Dioecesis Conversanensis-Monopolitana\n| local             = <!-- Name in the native language --> \n| image             = Conversano03.jpg\n| image_size        = 255px\n| image_alt         = \n| caption           = Cathedral in [[Conversano]]\n<!---- Locations ---->\n| country           = Italy\n| metropolitan      =  \n| territory         = \n| province          = [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto|Bari-Bitonto]]\n| coordinates       = <!-- Use {{coord}} --> \n<!---- Statistics ---->\n| area_km2          = 1,099 \n| population        = 252,707\n| population_as_of  = 2016\n| catholics         = 249,650 (guess)<!-- Number of Catholics in the diocese -->\n| catholics_percent = 98.8\n| parishes          = 56<!-- Number of parishes in the diocese -->\n| churches          = <!-- Number of churches in the diocese -->\n| congregations     = <!-- Number of congregations in the diocese -->\n| schools           = <!-- Number of church supported schools in the diocese -->\n| members           = <!-- Number of members in the diocese -->\n<!---- Information ---->\n| denomination      = [[Catholic Church]]\n| rite              = [[Roman Rite]]\n| established       = 5th Century \n| cathedral         = Basilica Cattedrale di S. Maria Assunta\n| cocathedral       = Basilica Cattedrale di Maria SS. della Mactia\n| patron            = \n| priests           = 94 (diocesan)<br />49 (Religious Orders)<br />17 Permanent Deacons<!-- Number of priests in the diocese -->\n<!---- Current leadership ---->\n| pope              = {{Incumbent pope}} <!-- DO NOT CHANGE. This will update the Popes Automatically as they change -->\n| bishop_title      = Bishop\n| bishop            = [[Giuseppe Favale]]\n| coadjutor         = \n| auxiliary_bishops = \n| vicar_general     = \n| emeritus_bishops  = \n<!---- Map ---->\n| map               = Regione ecclesiastica Puglia.PNG\n| map_alt           = Regional map of dioceses of east coast of Italy\n| map_caption       = \n<!---- Website ---->\n| website           = [http://www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it/ www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it]\n| footnotes         = \n}}\nThe Italian Roman Catholic '''diocese of Conversano-Monopoli''' ({{lang-la|Dioecesis Conversanensis-Monopolitana}}), in [[Apulia]], has existed since 1986, when the [[diocese of Monopoli]] was united with the historic '''diocese of Conversano'''. The diocese is a [[suffragan]] of the [[Archdiocese of Bari-Bitonto]].<ref name=CathHierMazaraConversano>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/diocese/dconv.html \"Diocese of Conversano-Monopoli\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref><ref name=GCathConversano>[http://www.gcatholic.org/dioceses/diocese/conv0.htm \"Diocese of Conversano\u2013Monopoli\"]  ''GCatholic.org''. Gabriel Chow. Retrieved February 29, 2016</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n[[Conversano]] is the ancient [[Cupersanum]]. After the invasion of the Normans, it was for a while the seat of a duchy; later, however, it became a fief of the [[dukes of Atri]].\n\nLocal tradition preserves the name of a bishop, Simplicius, who attended the Roman synod of 487 and died in 492, but he belongs to legend, not history.<ref>Lanzoni, p. 303, who notes that his name is not found in the acta of that synod.</ref> Ferdinando Ughelli<ref>''Italia sacra'' VII, p. 701.</ref> prints the narrative of Francesco Giuliano of Conversano concerning Simplicius, but states that it seems to him to be highly suspect, and maybe deliberately invented falsehoods or corrupt, since there are some things found in it which cannot be true.<ref>''...mihi valde suspecta videtur, et forte commentitia vel corrupta, cum in ea aliqua sint apposita quae cum veritate esse non possunt.''</ref>\n\nThe first alleged bishop of Conversano was [[Hilarius (bishop, fl. 501)|Hilarius]], present at the Roman synod of 501. His name however is a false reading of the acts of the synod; he actually belonged to Tempsa in the Abruzzi, not to Conversano in Apulia.\n\nNo other names are recorded up to the episcopate of Leo, mentioned in a document of 1088.\n\nIn 1670 (and 1744) the Chapter of the Cathedral of the Assumption of the Body of the Blessed Virgin Mary into Heaven was composed of four dignities (the Archdeacon, the Archpriest, the Cantor and the Primicerius<ref>Ughelli, p. 700.</ref>) and twenty-six Canons.<ref>Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 note 1; VI, p. 181 note 1. Ughelli says there were twelve Canons.</ref>  In the city of approximately 7,000 inhabitants (1744) there were five religious houses for men and three monasteries for men.\n\n==Bishops==\n===Diocese of Conversano===\n====to 1400====\n:'''...'''\n* Leo (attested 1088)<ref>Leo granted the spiritual jurisdiction of Castrum Puteneanum to the monastery of S. Stefano  in Monopoli. Ughelli, p. 704. Graevius-Burmann, pp. 39, 69.</ref>\n:'''...'''\n*Cafisius (attested 1179, 1180)<ref>Ughelli, p. 704. Kamp, p. 626.</ref>\n*Guilelmus (attested 1188 \u2013 April 1202)<ref>Ughelli, pp. 704-705. Kamp, p. 626.</ref>\n*''Ignotus'' (attested 1207)<ref>Kamp, pp. 626-627.</ref>\n*Concilius (attested April 1212 \u2013 9 October 1231)<ref>Kamp, pp. 627-628.</ref>\n* Stefano, O.Cist. (attested 1267 \u2013 1274)<ref name=NewAdvent>Umberto Benigni. \"[http://www.newadvent.org/cathen/04346a.htm Conversano].\" The Catholic Encyclopedia. Vol. 4. New York: Robert Appleton Company, 1908. Retrieved: 2016-10-02.  Ughelli, VII, pp. 705-708. Kamp, pp. 628-629.</ref>\n;'''...'''\n* Giovanni de Gropi (c. 1283)<ref>Gropi: Ughelli, pp. 711-712. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n;'''...'''\n* Guillelmus (attested 1318, 1321)<ref>Guillelmus: Gams, p. 877. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Petrus Baccari (attested 1335, 1342)<ref>Petrus Baccari: Gams, p. 877. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Stefano (7 January 1351 \u2013 1355?)<ref>Stefano: Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n* Petrus de Ytro (19 February 1356 \u2013 )\n* Guilelmus (Avignon Obedience)\n* Angelo de Cupersano, O.Min. (12 July 1393 \u2013 ) (Avignon Obedience)<ref>Angelo had previously been Bishop of Polignano (1382\u20131393). Eubel, I, pp. 218, 405.</ref>\n* Amicus (Antonius) (Roman Obedience)\n* Jacobus ( \u2013 22 December 1399) (Roman Obedience)<ref>Jacobus was transferred to the diocese of Guardialfiera on 22 December 1399. Eubel, I, pp. 218, 269.</ref>\n\n====1400 to 1600====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* Franciscus\n*Stefano de Alfano (9 March 1403 \u2013 1423)<ref>Stefano: Ughelli, p. 412. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n*Antonio Guidotti (9 Sep 1423 \u2013 1432 Died)<ref>Antonio was the son of Guidotti, a notary of Conversano. He was Archdeacon of Conversano when appointed bishop by [[Pope Martin IV]]. Ughelli, p. 412. Cappelletti, XXI, p. 42. Eubel, I, p. 218.</ref>\n:*Marino Orsini (4 November 1432 \u2013 29 April 1437) (Administrator)<ref>Orsini, son of Francesco Orsini, was a member of the aristocratic Roman family of the Orsini. He was a Doctor of Canon Law and a Protonotary Apostolic. On 4 July 1444 he was named Archbishop of Palermo, and then Archbishop of Taranto on 30 July 1445. He served as papal Nuncio in England. {{cite book|author=Jean Guiraud|title=L'\u00e9tat pontifical apr\u00e8s le grand schisme: \u00e9tude de g\u00e9ographie politique|url=https://archive.org/details/ltatpontificala00guirgoog|year=1896|publisher=A. Fontemoing|location=Paris|language=French|page=[https://archive.org/details/ltatpontificala00guirgoog/page/n134 116]}} Eubel, II, p. 136 with note 1; 211; 246.</ref>\n*[[Andrea Veroli]] (29 Apr 1437 \u2013 25 Sep 1439)<ref>Veroli was appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Campobasso-Boiano|Bishop of Boiano]] on 25 September 1439. Eubel, II, pp. 108, 135.</ref><ref name=CathHierAndVer>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bverul.html \"Bishop Andrea Veroli\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved May 10, 2017</ref>\n* Donato Bottini, [[O.E.S.A.]] (9 October 1439 \u2013 4 September 1448)<ref>A Neapolitan, Bishop Donato was transferred to the diocese of Valva on 4 September 1448. He was later Bishop of Urbino (1452), and Camerino (1464). Eubel, II, pp. 135, 262.</ref>\n*Pietro de Miggola, [[Order of Minims|O.M.]] (4 September 1448 \u2013 1464)<ref>Pietro was a Spaniard, and had been papal Penitentiary Minor. Ughelli, VII, p. 713.</ref>\n*Paolo de Torcoli (30 November 1465 \u2013 d. 1482)<ref>Torcoli was Capitular Vicar during the vacancy following the death of Bishop Pietro de Miggola. He was appointed bishop by [[Pope Paul II]] at the request of Count Giulio Acquaviva and Countess Catherine. Ughelli, p. 713. Eubel, II, p. 135.</ref>\n*[[Sulpicio Acquaviva d'Aragona]] (17 Feb 1483 \u2013 1494 Died)<ref>Sulpicio Acquaviva was the son of Giulio Antonio Acquaviva and Caterina d'Atri. The family of Acquaviva had been Counts of Conversano since the fifteenth century: {{cite book|author=Casimiro : di S. Maria Maddalena padre (padre)|title=Cronica della provincia de' Minori Osservanti Scalzi di S. Pietro d'Alcantara nel Regno di Napoli |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_zgSqJ-xk6ykC|year=1729|publisher=a spese di d. Lelio di Cabano|location=Naples|language=Italian|pages=[https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_zgSqJ-xk6ykC/page/n485 466]\u2013468}} {{cite book|author=Pierfrancesco Rescio|title=La Cattedrale di Conversano|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3PFHP07BDksC&pg=PA51|year=2001|publisher=Rubbettino Editore|language=Italian|isbn=978-88-498-0094-4|page=51}}</ref><ref name=CathHierSulpAcqua>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bacqdaras.html \"Bishop Sulpicio Acquaviva d'Aragona\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Pistacchio]] (1494 \u2013 3 Nov 1499 Appointed, [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Bitetto|Bishop of Bitetto]])<ref name=CathHierVinPista>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bpistacc.html \"Bishop Vincenzo Pistacchio\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved March 21, 2016</ref>\n*[[Donato Acquaviva d'Aragona]] (1499 \u2013 1528 Died)<ref>Donato was the brother of the Marquis de Bitonto and of Bishop Sulpicio Acquaviva.  Donato d'Aragona was appointed Bishop of Conversano at the age of 24, and thus was only ''Administrator'' of the diocese for three years, until he reached the age of 27, when he could be consecrated in accordance with Canon Law. He held the rank of Protonotary Apostolic. Eubel, II, p. 135, with note 3.</ref><ref name=CathHierDonAcqAra>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bacqdarad.html \"Bishop Donato Acquaviva d'Aragona\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*[[Antonio Sanseverino]], [[O.S.Io.Hieros.]] (28 Jul 1529 \u2013 11 Feb 1534 Resigned) \n*[[Giacomo Antonio Carrozza]] (1534 \u2013 1560 Died)<ref name=CathHierGiaAntCar>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcarroz.html \"Bishop Giacomo Antonio Carrozza\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*[[Giovanni Francesco Lottini]] (1560 \u2013 1561 Resigned) \n*[[Romolo de Valentibus]] (1561 \u2013 1579 Died)<ref name=CathHierRomValen>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bvlntbs.html \"Bishop Romolo de Valentibus\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved September 30, 2016</ref>\n*Francesco Maria Sforza (1579 \u2013 1605 Died)<ref>Francesco Sforza was a native of Monopoli and a doctor of theology. Ughelli, VII, p. 715. Eubel, III, p. 177.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====1600 to 1800====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*[[Pietro Capullio]], [[O.F.M. Conv.]] (31 Aug 1605 \u2013 24 Jun 1625 Died)<ref>Capulli was a native of Cortone. He was regent of the school at the convent of the Franciscans at the Basilica XII Apostolorum in Rome. He was named bishop of Conversano by [[Pope Paul V]] on 31 August 1605, and consecrated by Cardinal Evangelista Palotto on 14 September 1605. He died on 24 June 1625. Ughelli, p. 715. Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 2.</ref>\n*[[Vincenzo Martinelli (bishop)]], [[Order of Preachers|O.P.]] (18 Aug 1625 \u2013 20 Sep 1632)<ref>Bishop Martinelli was transferred to the diocese of  [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Venafro|Venafro]] on 20 September 1632. He died in August 1635. Gauchat, IV, pp. 163 with note 3; 361 with note 3.</ref>\n*[[Antonio Brunachio]] (24 Nov 1632 \u2013 1 Jan 1638 Died)<ref>Brunachio: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 4.</ref>\n*[[Agostino Ferentillo]] (19 Apr 1638 \u2013 7 Sep 1641 Died)<ref>Ferentillo: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 5.</ref>\n*[[Pietro Paolo Bonsi]] (26 May 1642 \u2013 1658 Died)<ref>Bonsi: Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 6.</ref>\n*[[Giuseppe Palermo]] (8 Dec 1658 \u2013 1 Sep 1670)<ref>Palermo was transferred to the diocese of [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Santa Severina|Santa Severina]] on 1 September 1670. He died in 1673. Gauchat, IV, p. 163 with note 7. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 355 with note 2.</ref>\n* Giovanni Stefano Sanarica (Senarega), [[Order of Saint Benedict|O.S.B.]] (23 Feb 1671 \u2013 16 Jun 1679 Died)<ref>Senarega was born in Albaro (diocese of Genoa). He held a doctorate in theology (Parma 1663). He was consecrated in Rome on 8 March 1671 by Cardinal Carlo Roberti. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 with note 2.</ref> \n*[[Andrea Brancaccio]], [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (13 Jan 1681 \u2013 18 Apr 1701)<ref>Appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of Cosenza-Bisignano|Archbishop of Cosenza]]. Ritzler-Sefrin, V, pp. 171 with note 3; 179 with note 4.</ref><ref name=CathHierNicCir>[http://www.catholic-hierarchy.org/bishop/bcirillo.html \"Bishop Nicola Cirillo\"] ''[[Catholic-Hierarchy.org]]''. David M. Cheney. Retrieved August 21, 2016.{{self-published inline|date=March 2017}}</ref>\n*Filippo Meda (23 Jan 1702 \u2013 18 Jul 1733 Died)<ref>Meda: Ritzler-Sefrin, V, p. 171 with note 4.</ref>\n*Giovanni Macario Valenti (28 Sep 1733 \u2013 10 Apr 1744 Died)<ref>Valenti: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 2.</ref>\n*Filippo Felice del Prete (13 Apr 1744 \u2013 22 Dec 1751 Died)<ref>Del Prete: Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 3.</ref>\n*Michele di Tarsia, [[C.P.O.]] (24 Jan 1752 \u2013 7 May 1772 Died)<ref>Born in 1696, Tarsia was a native of Conversano, and was ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (La Sapienza, Rome, 1752) at the age of 48. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 30 January 1752 by the titular Patriarch of Constantinople, Ferdinando Maria Rossi. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 4.</ref>\n*Fabio Maria Palumbo, [[Congregation of Clerics Regular of the Divine Providence|C.R.]] (7 Sep 1772 \u2013 18 Mar 1786 Died)<ref>Palumbo was born in 1708 at Lecce. He taught theology in several houses of his Congregation. He was Vicar of the house of his Congregation at S. Andrea della Valle in Rome. He was consecrated in Rome by Cardinal Ferdinando Maria Rossi on 13 September 1772. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 5.</ref>\n*Nicola Vecchi (27 Feb 1792 \u2013 18 Dec 1797)<ref>Vecchi was appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Teano|Bishop of Teano]] by Ferdinand I, King of the Two Sicilies, on 24 October 1797, and confirmed by Pope Pius VI on 18 December 1797. Ritzler-Sefrin, pp. 181 with note 6; 399 with note 8.</ref>\n{{div col end}}\n\n====1800 to 1986====\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n*Gennaro Carelli (18 Dec 1797 \u2013 3 Mar 1818 Died)<ref>Carelli was a native of Conversano. He held the degree of ''Doctor in utroque iure'' (Naples 1771). He was Canon, then Primicerius, and finally Archpriest of the Chapter of the Cathedral of Conversano. He was nominated bishop on 31 October 1797 by King [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies]], and approved by [[Pope Pius VI]] on 18 December 1797. Carelli was consecrated in Rome on 24 December 1797 by Cardinal Giovanni Battista Caprara. Luigi Valvalle, in D'Avino, p. 221. Ritzler-Sefrin, VI, p. 181 with note 7.</ref>\n*Nicola Carelli (21 Feb 1820 \u2013 14 Apr 1826 Died)<ref>Nicola Carelli was the brother of Bishop Gennaro Carelli.</ref>\n*Giovanni De Simone, [[Congregation of the Mission|C.M.]] (3 Jul 1826 \u2013 13 Aug 1847 Died)\n*Giuseppe-Maria Mucedola (11 Dec 1848 \u2013 22 Mar 1865 Died)<ref>Mucedola was born in San Paolo (diocese of Santa Severina) in 1807. As bishop, in 1861 he defended the right of the people to make their own political choices in a referendum on the Kingdom of Italy. {{cite book|author=Pietro Scoppola|title=Chiesa e Stato nella storia d'Italia: Storia documentaria dall'Unit\u0101 alla Republica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eoUcAAAAMAAJ|year=1967|publisher=Ed. Laterza|location=Roma|language=Italian|page=142}} {{cite book|author=Cosmo Francesco Ruppi|title=Giuseppe Maria Mucedola: vescovo-patriota di Conversano : con document inediti|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-DQQAQAAIAAJ|year=1965|publisher=Scuola Tip. Istituto Provinciale Apicella|location=Molfetta (Bari)|language=Italian}}</ref>\n*Salvatore Silvestris, [[C.SS.R.]] (23 Feb 1872 \u2013 14 Feb 1879 Died)\n*Augusto Antonio Vicentini (12 May 1879 \u2013 13 May 1881)<ref>Vicentini was born in L'Aquila in 1829. He was appointed [[Roman Catholic Archdiocese of L'Aquila|Archbishop of L\u2019Aquila]] on 13 May 1881. ''La Gerarchia cattolica 1882'' (Rome: Monaldi 1882), p. 108.</ref>\n*[[Casimiro Gennari]] (13 May 1881 \u2013 6 Feb 1897)<ref>Gennari was a native of Maratea (diocese of Policastro). He was the founder of the monthly journal ''Il Monitore ecclesiastico'', and was a noted author of books on ecclesiastical topics. He was consecrated a bishop in Rome on 15 May 1881 by Cardinal Edward Howard. He was appointed Titular Archbishop of Naupactus on 6 February 1897, and was named a Cardinal by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 15 April 1901.  Gennari was a collaborator in the creation of the 1917 Pio-Benedictine Code of Canon Law. As a Cardinal, and particularly as Prefect of the SC of the Council, he pressed for frequent reception of communion. He died on 31 January 1914. {{cite book|author=Joseph Dougherty|title=From Altar-Throne to Table: The Campaign for Frequent Holy Communion in the Catholic Church|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E3ZaJeZj-AsC&pg=PA83|year=2010|publisher=Scarecrow Press|location=Lanham MD USA|isbn=978-0-8108-7092-5|pages=82\u201383}} {{cite book|author=Harris M. Lentz III|title=Popes and Cardinals of the 20th Century: A Biographical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jXEwCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA216|year=2001|publisher=McFarland|location=Jefferson, NC USA|isbn=978-0-7864-4101-3|page=79}} G. di Ruocco, ''Il Cardinale Casimiro Gennari. Pastore e giurista (1839\u20131914) (Naples: Laurentiana 1995).</ref>\n*Antonio Lamberti (19 Apr 1897 \u2013 12 Aug 1917 Died)\n*Domenico Lancellotti (14 Mar 1918 \u2013 9 Jun 1930 Died)\n*Domenico Argnani (30 Sep 1931 \u2013 15 Jun 1935)<ref>Argnani was appointed [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Macerata-Tolentino|Bishop of Macerata e Tolentino]] on 15 Jun 1935.</ref>\n*Gregorio Falconieri (12 Sep 1935 \u2013 24 May 1964 Retired)\n*Antonio D'Erchia (21 Jan 1970 \u2013 30 Sep 1986) (Appointed Bishop of the renamed Conversano-Monopoli)\n{{div col end}}\n\n[[File:Cattedrale 008.JPG|thumb|160px|Co-cathedral in [[Monopoli]]]]\n===Diocese of Conversano-Monopoli===\n''United: 30 September 1986 with [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Monopoli|Diocese of Monopoli]]''\n*Antonio D'Erchia (30 Sep 1986 \u2013 11 Feb 1987 Retired)\n*[[Domenico Padovano]] (13 Feb 1987 \u2013 5 Feb 2016 Retired) \n*Giuseppe Favale (5 Feb 2016 \u2013 )<ref>Diocesi di Conversano Monopoli, [http://www.conversano.chiesacattolica.it/vescovo/ ''S. E. Mons Giuseppe Favale''], retrieved: 2017-03-12.{{in lang|it}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==Books==\n===Reference Works===\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia catholica, Tomus 1|date=1913|publisher=Libreria Regensbergiana|location=M\u00fcnster|edition=second|url=https://archive.org/details/hierarchiacathol01eubeuoft}} (in Latin)\n*{{cite book|last1=Eubel|first1=Conradus (ed.)|title=Hierarchia